Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.584
 

00:00:01.584 --> 00:00:03.000
MICHAEL WEISS-MALIK:
Hi everybody.

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:03.650
Hear me OK?

00:00:03.650 --> 00:00:05.770
OK, so I think we're
going to get going.

00:00:05.770 --> 00:00:07.920
My name's Michael Weiss-Malik.

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:11.770
Our guest today,
Jonathan Kuniholm.

00:00:11.770 --> 00:00:15.480
I met him in we think 2007--
as far as we can piece back

00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:17.720
together-- at a
SciFoo conference

00:00:17.720 --> 00:00:20.380
and he had some pretty cool
tech that he was demoing.

00:00:20.380 --> 00:00:24.390
Some open source robotics
stuff related to prosthetics.

00:00:24.390 --> 00:00:26.380
And I was impressed
enough that I said,

00:00:26.380 --> 00:00:29.020
hey you should come and give
a talk at Google some time.

00:00:29.020 --> 00:00:33.240
And he took that to heart and
about four or five years later

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:35.800
emailed me and said, hey you
offered that talk at Google,

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:37.670
now would be a great time.

00:00:37.670 --> 00:00:40.000
So so we're hosting him today.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.640
Jonathan is the president and
founder of the open prosthetics

00:00:43.640 --> 00:00:44.530
project.

00:00:44.530 --> 00:00:47.670
He's also a founder of
StumpworX, a startup that

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:49.987
focuses on prosthetic
technology.

00:00:49.987 --> 00:00:52.320
He's also presidential appointee
to the National Council

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:53.810
on Disability.

00:00:53.810 --> 00:00:56.250
And the stuff he has
to say is pretty cool.

00:00:56.250 --> 00:00:57.751
So please put your
hands together

00:00:57.751 --> 00:00:58.750
and help me welcome Jon.

00:00:58.750 --> 00:01:03.230
 

00:01:03.230 --> 00:01:06.900
JON KUNIHOLM: Thanks
very much, Michael.

00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:10.630
Let me first just
offer a disclaimer

00:01:10.630 --> 00:01:12.140
with respect to my
government job--

00:01:12.140 --> 00:01:15.760
they encourage us to do this--
that everything that I'm

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:18.890
going to say today
are my personal views

00:01:18.890 --> 00:01:22.770
and not reflective of any
position of the government.

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:25.610
 

00:01:25.610 --> 00:01:29.110
So what I would like
to talk about today

00:01:29.110 --> 00:01:36.760
is how we can design good
design to solve problems

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:40.480
that society has for
the most part neglected.

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:44.290
And I came across
one of those problems

00:01:44.290 --> 00:01:48.200
personally after I
lost my arm in 2005

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:51.310
and discovered that
prosthetic arms were

00:01:51.310 --> 00:01:53.620
an orphan medical device.

00:01:53.620 --> 00:01:56.220
And in thinking
a little bit more

00:01:56.220 --> 00:02:02.610
about why prosthetic arms lagged
so far behind other technology

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:06.350
that we use every day,
I started to realize

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:10.720
that prosthetic arms and
orphan medical devices

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:16.040
are part of a larger
group of those problems

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:20.310
that society has
tended to neglect,

00:02:20.310 --> 00:02:22.590
which can be solved by
something that we're beginning

00:02:22.590 --> 00:02:25.480
to call public interest design.

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:29.300
And the question that I'd really
like to talk about today--

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:32.040
and I would actually
like it to be

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:35.610
the beginning of a discussion
because it's something that

00:02:35.610 --> 00:02:40.170
by no means I claim to
have even begun to solve--

00:02:40.170 --> 00:02:44.510
is, how can we marshal
all of the tools

00:02:44.510 --> 00:02:49.510
at our disposal to trying to
better solve those problems.

00:02:49.510 --> 00:02:54.130
Because very much now I believe
that most of those problems

00:02:54.130 --> 00:02:58.020
are solved in kind
of a haphazard way.

00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:02.600
Government funded projects,
philanthropy, side

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:06.240
projects from industry.

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:10.960
You name the way that people
happen upon these issues

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:13.210
and try to solve them,
but in general you

00:03:13.210 --> 00:03:18.010
can be sure that the resources
and attention that we devote

00:03:18.010 --> 00:03:20.680
toward solving these
underserved needs

00:03:20.680 --> 00:03:24.690
are going to lag far
behind those problems which

00:03:24.690 --> 00:03:29.210
are very obvious from every
other standpoint need solving.

00:03:29.210 --> 00:03:31.340
Very profitable things.

00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:34.500
There was no question
that cell phone technology

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:39.600
was going to improve over the
last 10 years, for example.

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:47.140
So in the summer of 2005 I
took leave from graduate school

00:03:47.140 --> 00:03:52.650
at Duke University and I was
deployed as a marine to Iraq

00:03:52.650 --> 00:03:53.540
in Anbar Province.

00:03:53.540 --> 00:03:56.560
 

00:03:56.560 --> 00:04:01.350
And I was the platoon commander
for an engineer position of 50

00:04:01.350 --> 00:04:07.180
Marines and we were doing
mostly what everybody

00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:09.770
was doing over there, which
was sustainment and stability

00:04:09.770 --> 00:04:15.460
operations, patrolling, guarding
convoys, that sort of thing.

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:22.380
On New Year's day of 2005
I was on a foot patrol

00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:26.205
that was ambushed by
improvised explosive device.

00:04:26.205 --> 00:04:29.640
 

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:34.180
The blast took off
most of my forearm

00:04:34.180 --> 00:04:39.510
and I found myself back
in the States and learning

00:04:39.510 --> 00:04:42.280
about prosthetic arm technology.

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:45.430
 

00:04:45.430 --> 00:04:48.890
I managed to get
myself back to school

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:52.650
and get involved with a
research project sponsored

00:04:52.650 --> 00:04:55.110
by DARPA called the
Revolutionizing Prosthetics

00:04:55.110 --> 00:04:56.280
2009 Project.

00:04:56.280 --> 00:04:59.240
It was one of two that
DARPA was funding.

00:04:59.240 --> 00:05:04.930
Which is really the first
serious prosthetic arm research

00:05:04.930 --> 00:05:07.560
effort that had occurred
in the United States

00:05:07.560 --> 00:05:11.530
since-- there was a
small one in the '70s--

00:05:11.530 --> 00:05:13.320
but really since World War II.

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:19.420
 

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:22.170
The goal was a
really ambitious one.

00:05:22.170 --> 00:05:28.270
The goal was to create--
in four years, in 2007--

00:05:28.270 --> 00:05:31.320
an arm using commercially
available technology

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:35.910
that could go to market
in that year, in 2007.

00:05:35.910 --> 00:05:38.840
And then more
ambitiously to create

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:41.260
an arm that had more
degrees of freedom,

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:43.840
was fully in neurally
integrated-- so

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:47.920
nearly the same articulation
as a native human arm--

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:49.445
and full strength.

00:05:49.445 --> 00:05:52.340
 

00:05:52.340 --> 00:05:56.340
An incredibly ambitious project.

00:05:56.340 --> 00:05:59.030
What I think it's
important to understand

00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:01.750
there's been an enormous--
and this picture

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:04.450
is up here not too bag
that I was on 60 Minutes,

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:08.590
but to show the
kind of attention

00:06:08.590 --> 00:06:11.940
to that these projects got.

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:13.960
For whatever reason,
prosthetic arms

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:17.960
tend to really capture
the popular imagination.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:20.360
People love robotics.

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:24.480
They love thinking about the
barriers, the singularity

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:26.850
and the barriers between man
and machine disappearing.

00:06:26.850 --> 00:06:29.850
It becomes a vehicle for
all kinds of philosophical

00:06:29.850 --> 00:06:32.380
and science fiction interest.

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:38.210
I think the takeaway about
these projects, which

00:06:38.210 --> 00:06:42.070
is important to
remember is first of all

00:06:42.070 --> 00:06:47.840
that despite the amazing things
that both of these research

00:06:47.840 --> 00:06:53.380
efforts accomplished,
we still have not--

00:06:53.380 --> 00:06:57.810
more than 10 years since the
war began in Afghanistan,

00:06:57.810 --> 00:07:02.220
actually pushing 15
now-- still do not

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:05.730
have any commercially
available device that's

00:07:05.730 --> 00:07:10.640
resulted from any of this
government funded research.

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:14.090
We're still waiting
for the first one.

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:17.420
It has remained, as always,
just around the corner.

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:23.152
And I'm told that we're waiting
on FDA approval for the DECA RP

00:07:23.152 --> 00:07:27.190
'07 project to
receive FDA approval.

00:07:27.190 --> 00:07:29.950
And it has been
some clinical trials

00:07:29.950 --> 00:07:32.560
but we still haven't
seen a device.

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:34.800
The other one is
I think that it's

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:39.330
important to understand-- it's
my belief that we have a media

00:07:39.330 --> 00:07:40.770
bias.

00:07:40.770 --> 00:07:44.310
It's not a political
conservative media bias,

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:46.230
but it's one towards
entertainment.

00:07:46.230 --> 00:07:50.640
And so the word
bionic is used a lot,

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:54.250
the words dexterous
and manipulation

00:07:54.250 --> 00:07:58.290
are also used a lot, which
have very specific meanings

00:07:58.290 --> 00:07:59.120
in robotics.

00:07:59.120 --> 00:08:07.620
 

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:10.590
There are some caveats
that I could give.

00:08:10.590 --> 00:08:15.190
You could call a trigger
grip for example,

00:08:15.190 --> 00:08:18.350
where one part of
the hand is grasping

00:08:18.350 --> 00:08:22.000
a handle of a cordless
drill and the finger is

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.220
pulling the trigger.

00:08:24.220 --> 00:08:27.960
That tends toward
sort of manipulation.

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:29.350
It's at least a compound grasp.

00:08:29.350 --> 00:08:30.766
For one part of
your hand is doing

00:08:30.766 --> 00:08:32.220
one thing and one doing another.

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:37.549
Of course the slide that
I'm showing here right now

00:08:37.549 --> 00:08:42.860
gives you some insight into what
the human hands are capable of.

00:08:42.860 --> 00:08:45.270
This pair of hands
is doing a card trick

00:08:45.270 --> 00:08:50.860
where four cuts of the
deck are being controlled

00:08:50.860 --> 00:08:53.370
by different parts
of the two hands

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:54.780
and it's a dynamic movement.

00:08:54.780 --> 00:08:57.880
 

00:08:57.880 --> 00:09:02.800
I guarantee you that there isn't
a robotic hand of any kind that

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:05.040
could do these card
tricks right now.

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:10.410
But based on the popular
press presentation of all this

00:09:10.410 --> 00:09:13.090
you would think that it can.

00:09:13.090 --> 00:09:16.000
You would think that
these problems are solved.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.690
So while I think it's important
to acknowledge the strides that

00:09:20.690 --> 00:09:23.040
were made by these
research projects,

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:24.830
it's also very
important to understand

00:09:24.830 --> 00:09:26.150
that we are not there yet.

00:09:26.150 --> 00:09:31.700
And we do not have
bionic people.

00:09:31.700 --> 00:09:36.700
And these hands are for
the most part right now,

00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:40.440
I think that it would be fair
to say, at least in terms

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:45.780
of prosthetic control that even
these highly articulated hands

00:09:45.780 --> 00:09:48.090
are really only
capable of grasping.

00:09:48.090 --> 00:09:50.530
And the difference between
grasping and manipulation I

00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:55.130
think you can use a
Rubik's cube to illustrate.

00:09:55.130 --> 00:10:00.400
Manipulation is a speed
cuber solving a Rubik's cube

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:06.030
in a few minutes and
grasping is not dropping it.

00:10:06.030 --> 00:10:08.690
And grasping a Rubik's
cube is actually something

00:10:08.690 --> 00:10:12.360
that I can do with
the hook that I

00:10:12.360 --> 00:10:15.440
wear when I do wear
a prosthetic arm.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:19.080
Which is the Dorrance
5x named after the guy

00:10:19.080 --> 00:10:21.840
who patented in 1912.

00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:28.620
And you can see that since
then it's evolved a little bit.

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:34.230
There's some rubber grip on
the fingers a cigarette notch--

00:10:34.230 --> 00:10:38.000
and I think it's
called a pen notch now.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.680
But this remains
despite everything

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:45.730
that's happened the most
used prosthetic terminal

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:47.360
device in America.

00:10:47.360 --> 00:10:51.540
And were you to go to the
Myoelectric conference

00:10:51.540 --> 00:10:56.330
in New Brunswick in Canada this
August it would be a fair bet

00:10:56.330 --> 00:11:00.220
to make that the majority
of amputees attending

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:02.410
the conference-- at least
the ones who weren't paid

00:11:02.410 --> 00:11:04.860
to be there by a
prosthetic company--

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:06.920
would be wearing
one of these devices

00:11:06.920 --> 00:11:10.430
and not any of the
robotic prosthetic hands

00:11:10.430 --> 00:11:11.820
that are available.

00:11:11.820 --> 00:11:14.280
The other thing that's
important to note about this

00:11:14.280 --> 00:11:17.920
is that there's another
choice which actually beats

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:20.940
all of them, which is the
one that I'm wearing today,

00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:23.890
which is nothing.

00:11:23.890 --> 00:11:28.170
About half of all arm
amputees choose most times not

00:11:28.170 --> 00:11:29.470
to wear prosthesis at all.

00:11:29.470 --> 00:11:31.990
And it's mostly because
of weight and comfort

00:11:31.990 --> 00:11:34.520
in suspension and I'm going to
talk about that a little bit

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:35.020
later.

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:45.970
 

00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:48.990
Now why is all of that?

00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:55.590
This is by no means an
attack on any the folks

00:11:55.590 --> 00:11:58.880
who were generous enough
to fund that project

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:00.810
and try to make some progress.

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:03.430
The real problem is that
they're there simply

00:12:03.430 --> 00:12:06.500
isn't a market for these things.

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:11.280
The market for powered arms
it is just barely noise

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:13.990
compared to these
other large markets.

00:12:13.990 --> 00:12:17.450
And even though the government
has accomplished quite a bit

00:12:17.450 --> 00:12:19.670
in some of these
research projects, what

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:23.930
we call the valley of death,
which is the bridge that one

00:12:23.930 --> 00:12:28.020
of these products must cross
in order to get from the lab

00:12:28.020 --> 00:12:31.740
into becoming a clinical
product is really significant.

00:12:31.740 --> 00:12:40.395
And without a market to
drive further funding,

00:12:40.395 --> 00:12:43.500
that gap-- which is estimated
by people in the industry

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:47.600
to be something like
90% of the R&amp;D remaining

00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:50.750
on a medical product once a
proof of principal device is

00:12:50.750 --> 00:12:55.470
finished-- there's just simply
nowhere for those resources

00:12:55.470 --> 00:12:57.560
to come from and make it happen.

00:12:57.560 --> 00:13:00.350
 

00:13:00.350 --> 00:13:03.260
Correspondingly,
the amount of effort

00:13:03.260 --> 00:13:06.500
that's actually put into
solving this problem

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:08.760
is also very small.

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:13.340
Compared to-- I cherry picked
a few really large government

00:13:13.340 --> 00:13:16.150
sponsored engineering projects.

00:13:16.150 --> 00:13:20.260
Some of which have been compared
to this DARPA prosthetics

00:13:20.260 --> 00:13:22.580
project.

00:13:22.580 --> 00:13:24.640
This is all in 2006 dollars.

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:27.730
The Manhattan Project
comes in over $20 billion,

00:13:27.730 --> 00:13:33.080
the moon race over $120 billion,
and just the R&amp;D for the Joint

00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:36.660
Strike Fighter at
over $40 billion.

00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:42.800
And so the $100 million, while
more than anybody had spent on

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:48.220
and on prosthetic arms in half
a century, the DARPA spend

00:13:48.220 --> 00:13:50.870
is basically just
noise compared to this.

00:13:50.870 --> 00:13:57.660
And I would argue that the
task that they set out to solve

00:13:57.660 --> 00:14:01.204
rivals some of these in
terms of the engineering

00:14:01.204 --> 00:14:01.870
effort required.

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:08.800
I mean it's a small project and
it and instead of a large one.

00:14:08.800 --> 00:14:15.080
But nevertheless an enormous
portion of our brains,

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:21.190
for example, is devoted to
the control of our hands

00:14:21.190 --> 00:14:21.927
in manipulation.

00:14:21.927 --> 00:14:23.302
I don't know if
you all have ever

00:14:23.302 --> 00:14:24.968
seen-- I don't have
a slide of it here--

00:14:24.968 --> 00:14:28.870
but the homunculus that neural
researchers use to represent.

00:14:28.870 --> 00:14:33.300
They take a human figure and
adjust him proportionally

00:14:33.300 --> 00:14:35.260
based on the number
of nerve endings

00:14:35.260 --> 00:14:36.550
in some studies of the brain.

00:14:36.550 --> 00:14:41.210
So this little figure has
gigantic lips, gigantic hands,

00:14:41.210 --> 00:14:44.720
and depending on whether you're
looking at the censored version

00:14:44.720 --> 00:14:46.980
or not, gigantic
genitalia, reflecting

00:14:46.980 --> 00:14:48.530
how much of our
brains are devoted

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:52.090
to control these
parts of our body.

00:14:52.090 --> 00:14:55.370
And this is true both in
terms of motor control

00:14:55.370 --> 00:14:57.490
and sensory control,
it works both ways.

00:14:57.490 --> 00:15:01.800
And as you can see from that
slide of the card trick,

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:04.130
feedback-- sensory
feedback-- is certainly

00:15:04.130 --> 00:15:09.850
a huge part of our hands
being able to do what we do.

00:15:09.850 --> 00:15:17.390
So what we have is
a three-way market

00:15:17.390 --> 00:15:21.340
failure to solve this problem.

00:15:21.340 --> 00:15:26.500
Industry, government, and
academia all doing their parts

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:28.950
but all unable to
solve this problem.

00:15:28.950 --> 00:15:33.970
 

00:15:33.970 --> 00:15:36.540
But of course it's
completely understandable

00:15:36.540 --> 00:15:39.990
and that's why we
call prosthetic arms

00:15:39.990 --> 00:15:40.970
an orphan device.

00:15:40.970 --> 00:15:50.950
The orphan drug law that was
passed in 1983 defined patients

00:15:50.950 --> 00:15:57.030
in need of a drug as
being medical orphans

00:15:57.030 --> 00:16:02.240
of their patient population
was less than 250,000.

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:04.690
So prosthetic arms
in the United States

00:16:04.690 --> 00:16:07.750
are about a couple
years ago, 43,000.

00:16:07.750 --> 00:16:11.280
So fewer than 50,000 patients
in the United States.

00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:17.170
That's a sixth of the maximum
threshold for being an orphan.

00:16:17.170 --> 00:16:21.920
Of course the orphan drug law
covers pharmaceuticals and not

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:22.720
medical devices.

00:16:22.720 --> 00:16:27.670
So we don't have a companion
regulation or law or anything

00:16:27.670 --> 00:16:31.330
that covers the creation
of medical devices.

00:16:31.330 --> 00:16:35.060
And another peculiarity
of course of that,

00:16:35.060 --> 00:16:39.620
is how we pay for medical
devices in the United States.

00:16:39.620 --> 00:16:43.470
And get to that will get
to that a little bit later.

00:16:43.470 --> 00:16:47.690
So as I mentioned before,
all of these medical orphans

00:16:47.690 --> 00:16:54.760
and the NIH-- and this includes
all of the orphan drug patient

00:16:54.760 --> 00:16:58.160
populations and others--
the NIH lists something

00:16:58.160 --> 00:17:01.430
