00:19:56.690 --> 00:19:59.640
But all of these
patients are underserved

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:03.260
in some way or another.

00:20:03.260 --> 00:20:05.700
So a good phrase
that's been used

00:20:05.700 --> 00:20:10.270
to describe all of these
problems and the design

00:20:10.270 --> 00:20:12.060
that we can use to
try to attack them,

00:20:12.060 --> 00:20:13.950
is Public Interest Design.

00:20:13.950 --> 00:20:15.490
Design in the public interest.

00:20:15.490 --> 00:20:18.590
And so really what
I'd like to talk

00:20:18.590 --> 00:20:22.350
about is, what are the
ways besides-- we'll

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:25.580
start off with government
sponsored research

00:20:25.580 --> 00:20:29.330
because that's a lot of
what's happening currently.

00:20:29.330 --> 00:20:32.500
What is our whole
quiver of tools

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:35.540
that we might use to try to
solve some of these problems?

00:20:35.540 --> 00:20:38.310
 

00:20:38.310 --> 00:20:39.310
Yeah, sorry about that.

00:20:39.310 --> 00:20:42.950
 

00:20:42.950 --> 00:20:45.300
What are the collection
of tools that we

00:20:45.300 --> 00:20:48.050
could use to try to better
solve these problems?

00:20:48.050 --> 00:20:50.460
And I, like lots of
people do, I think

00:20:50.460 --> 00:20:55.330
I'll probably come down on there
being some combination of all

00:20:55.330 --> 00:20:57.490
of these that are necessary.

00:20:57.490 --> 00:21:00.720
But just to brush over
them all-- to begin with,

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:03.810
government sponsored research
and commercialization.

00:21:03.810 --> 00:21:08.860
Then DIY and the maker culture.

00:21:08.860 --> 00:21:11.600
Potentially an orphan
device law to serve

00:21:11.600 --> 00:21:15.320
as a companion to
the orphan drug law

00:21:15.320 --> 00:21:19.300
that we've had in this
country since 1983.

00:21:19.300 --> 00:21:22.670
And then what other
regulatory or policy changes

00:21:22.670 --> 00:21:27.610
might be made under
our existing structure,

00:21:27.610 --> 00:21:31.289
but by program managers
who fund for example,

00:21:31.289 --> 00:21:33.080
some of this government
sponsored research.

00:21:33.080 --> 00:21:39.190
What things might they
do to try to raise

00:21:39.190 --> 00:21:41.490
the impact of the
research funding

00:21:41.490 --> 00:21:43.370
that they're
currently giving out?

00:21:43.370 --> 00:21:46.740
And then secondly what can
we do in the private sector?

00:21:46.740 --> 00:21:50.840
Are there ways that folks
in the private sector

00:21:50.840 --> 00:21:52.690
might be able to
contribute in ways

00:21:52.690 --> 00:21:56.820
that don't impact
their own bottom line?

00:21:56.820 --> 00:21:59.780
And they can in a
potentially even

00:21:59.780 --> 00:22:07.710
have a win-win in serving
these underserved folks.

00:22:07.710 --> 00:22:13.110
So to start off
with, these are icons

00:22:13.110 --> 00:22:15.910
that represent the three
major engineering research

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:18.860
efforts that I showed
the funding levels for.

00:22:18.860 --> 00:22:22.470
The moonshot, the atomic bomb,
and the Joint Strike Fighter.

00:22:22.470 --> 00:22:26.700
And it's certainly clear
that there are some problems

00:22:26.700 --> 00:22:30.510
that government has
to solve, if they're

00:22:30.510 --> 00:22:32.470
going to get solved for us.

00:22:32.470 --> 00:22:37.330
While we do have SpaceX in
a commercial space effort

00:22:37.330 --> 00:22:41.940
right now, it only exists
because the government

00:22:41.940 --> 00:22:43.850
is choosing to create
that capability

00:22:43.850 --> 00:22:46.269
in the fundings coming
from the government.

00:22:46.269 --> 00:22:47.810
So that's an example
actually of sort

00:22:47.810 --> 00:22:50.320
of spreading the stuff
around a little bit.

00:22:50.320 --> 00:22:56.220
But it was clear that
sending a man to the moon

00:22:56.220 --> 00:22:59.160
or building the bomb,
however you feel about

00:22:59.160 --> 00:23:02.200
that having done, these were
certainly projects they would

00:23:02.200 --> 00:23:06.640
never have happened had not one
of the largest and wealthiest

00:23:06.640 --> 00:23:08.390
governments in the
world decided that they

00:23:08.390 --> 00:23:09.650
were going to make it happen.

00:23:09.650 --> 00:23:14.800
And they happen because in
at least two in these cases--

00:23:14.800 --> 00:23:17.860
the first two that I
mentioned-- the results were

00:23:17.860 --> 00:23:19.050
non-negotiable.

00:23:19.050 --> 00:23:22.970
We were going to get to the
moon no matter how much it costs

00:23:22.970 --> 00:23:26.250
and how dangerous it was.

00:23:26.250 --> 00:23:31.090
Those who are in charge of the
bomb viewed it as a response

00:23:31.090 --> 00:23:37.150
to an existential threat and
that failure was not an option.

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:41.140
The government probably
would have spent anything

00:23:41.140 --> 00:23:46.120
to achieve these ends.

00:23:46.120 --> 00:23:51.370
Now a lot of times some
of these very programs

00:23:51.370 --> 00:23:54.080
and the other basic science
research that the government

00:23:54.080 --> 00:23:59.450
does are cited as having
intangible benefits that

00:23:59.450 --> 00:24:02.410
spin off, that we
would be without

00:24:02.410 --> 00:24:07.700
were it not for
these other efforts.

00:24:07.700 --> 00:24:10.120
So Tang, Teflon, and
Velcro are three.

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:12.110
And there's actually
a myth-busting page

00:24:12.110 --> 00:24:14.820
on NASA's website that I
have up there on the slide.

00:24:14.820 --> 00:24:18.300
It says that in fact, none
of these three products

00:24:18.300 --> 00:24:21.280
were created by NASA or
NASA-funded research.

00:24:21.280 --> 00:24:25.420
Although the space program did
take advantage of all of those.

00:24:25.420 --> 00:24:27.960
While they used Tang,
Teflon, and Velcro,

00:24:27.960 --> 00:24:29.380
they did not create it.

00:24:29.380 --> 00:24:34.560
And I would argue
that even if they had,

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:37.160
building upon sending
somebody the moon

00:24:37.160 --> 00:24:41.950
or building a high
tech fighter jet,

00:24:41.950 --> 00:24:44.070
are not the most efficient
ways to create things

00:24:44.070 --> 00:24:46.100
like Tang, Teflon, and Velcro.

00:24:46.100 --> 00:24:50.620
So if what you want
is a prosthetic arm

00:24:50.620 --> 00:24:56.640
or to put somebody on the moon
or to build a fighter jet,

00:24:56.640 --> 00:24:58.110
that is what you do.

00:24:58.110 --> 00:25:01.300
 

00:25:01.300 --> 00:25:03.640
This really comes
down to the difference

00:25:03.640 --> 00:25:07.050
between engineering
and basic science.

00:25:07.050 --> 00:25:10.740
So the point is that
whatever efforts there

00:25:10.740 --> 00:25:12.760
are that are devoted to
solving this problem,

00:25:12.760 --> 00:25:16.390
it really needs to be dedicated
to solving the problem.

00:25:16.390 --> 00:25:18.950
And there needs to be
some agreement on actually

00:25:18.950 --> 00:25:21.160
what the problem is.

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:27.720
A significant component at
least the four-year DARPA effort

00:25:27.720 --> 00:25:31.035
was based on the creation of a
neural brain-machine interface.

00:25:31.035 --> 00:25:35.530
 

00:25:35.530 --> 00:25:38.235
While in the long term
it's certainly true

00:25:38.235 --> 00:25:41.750
that that represents
potentially a holy grail

00:25:41.750 --> 00:25:46.150
of prosthetic arms,
it's not clear

00:25:46.150 --> 00:25:50.000
that is a necessary
component of it.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:52.870
Particularly given the
state of technology

00:25:52.870 --> 00:25:55.330
that most people
are using every day.

