00:31:53.530 --> 00:31:57.770
about a high school
student who has 3D printed

00:31:57.770 --> 00:32:02.040
a prosthetic hand that is
supposedly better than you pick

00:32:02.040 --> 00:32:04.980
the price point of
some commercially

00:32:04.980 --> 00:32:07.770
available prosthetic hand.

00:32:07.770 --> 00:32:13.360
There's really no scrutiny at
all that's applied to these

00:32:13.360 --> 00:32:14.510
claims .

00:32:14.510 --> 00:32:16.890
Very often there are
completely externally powered

00:32:16.890 --> 00:32:24.270
like motors with strings or
maybe they're not even powered.

00:32:24.270 --> 00:32:28.160
In any case, nobody really
closely examines the claim

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:33.290
that some kid has bested
a $40,000 prosthetic

00:32:33.290 --> 00:32:35.810
hand in his bedroom
with a RepRap machine.

00:32:35.810 --> 00:32:39.680
 

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:43.087
While I consider
myself to be a part of,

00:32:43.087 --> 00:32:44.670
and I fully embrace
the maker culture,

00:32:44.670 --> 00:32:48.400
I think we also need to be
very realistic about what we've

00:32:48.400 --> 00:32:50.970
actually accomplished
and try not

00:32:50.970 --> 00:32:54.680
to run victory laps before
we've actually done it.

00:32:54.680 --> 00:32:58.520
And I and I think that this
probably is one of those cases.

00:32:58.520 --> 00:33:01.720
Now that the happy
ending to this story

00:33:01.720 --> 00:33:04.980
is that there actually is
a prosthetic company called

00:33:04.980 --> 00:33:05.480
ToughWare.

00:33:05.480 --> 00:33:09.310
 

00:33:09.310 --> 00:33:12.780
They re-engineered this and
fixed some of the problems

00:33:12.780 --> 00:33:15.745
that we had actually identified
with the original design.

00:33:15.745 --> 00:33:17.120
I think you could
actually see it

00:33:17.120 --> 00:33:22.420
in the-- that's an original hook
from many decades ago up there.

00:33:22.420 --> 00:33:26.030
And you can see the
places it's been welded.

00:33:26.030 --> 00:33:30.730
And so this company fixed
some of the problems

00:33:30.730 --> 00:33:33.640
and where these
things were breaking.

00:33:33.640 --> 00:33:36.380
I do believe that
you can actually now

00:33:36.380 --> 00:33:41.450
purchase a version of this
hook commercially again.

00:33:41.450 --> 00:33:44.960
I consider that to
be a success even

00:33:44.960 --> 00:33:46.810
if we weren't the
ones who did it.

00:33:46.810 --> 00:33:49.710
 

00:33:49.710 --> 00:33:54.840
So lastly and then there
is some bleed across here--

00:33:54.840 --> 00:33:59.570
Michael did reference the
company that I've started.

00:33:59.570 --> 00:34:02.700
I also decided to
back up a little bit

00:34:02.700 --> 00:34:07.610
and solve one of the problems
about prosthetic arms that

00:34:07.610 --> 00:34:10.969
may be in fact the most vexing
and least addressed, which

00:34:10.969 --> 00:34:12.765
is how we attach them
to people's bodies.

00:34:12.765 --> 00:34:15.580
 

00:34:15.580 --> 00:34:19.520
This is traditionally done with
a hard carbon fiber or glass

00:34:19.520 --> 00:34:27.250
socket, a rubber liner and
maybe a plastic socket there.

00:34:27.250 --> 00:34:30.650
And I would liken a
lot of these designs

00:34:30.650 --> 00:34:34.040
to wearing wooden
shoes and rubber socks.

00:34:34.040 --> 00:34:37.489
And it does pretty horrible
things to your skin

00:34:37.489 --> 00:34:40.610
when there's moisture
and friction involved.

00:34:40.610 --> 00:34:44.190
And heat, moisture, weight,
and perceived weight

00:34:44.190 --> 00:34:47.190
is really related to
all of these things,

00:34:47.190 --> 00:34:50.027
because people will tolerate
hanging less off of your body

00:34:50.027 --> 00:34:51.360
when it doesn't really fit well.

00:34:51.360 --> 00:34:55.090
It feels like it's heavier
if it's uncomfortable.

00:34:55.090 --> 00:35:00.180
So we decided that
the way to solve this

00:35:00.180 --> 00:35:02.800
was to go back to what
prosthetic arms used

00:35:02.800 --> 00:35:04.660
to be like in the
'40s before the VA did

00:35:04.660 --> 00:35:08.310
all the research that created
these composite sockets

00:35:08.310 --> 00:35:12.800
and consider making prosthetic
sockets more like shoes.

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:14.634
Like athletic shoes.

00:35:14.634 --> 00:35:16.550
Prosthetic sockets used
to be made of leather,

00:35:16.550 --> 00:35:19.325
and I've been told
by old guys who

00:35:19.325 --> 00:35:20.700
wear leather
sockets that they're

00:35:20.700 --> 00:35:22.000
the most comfortable
thing in the world

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:23.860
and they would never
wear anything else.

00:35:23.860 --> 00:35:26.111
But you can't find anybody
to make one of these things

00:35:26.111 --> 00:35:27.943
now, because they're
really labor intensive.

00:35:27.943 --> 00:35:29.980
And the VA actually do a
whole bunch of research

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:34.024
in the '40s trying to figure
out how to make them not stink.

00:35:34.024 --> 00:35:35.565
Because they're
basically like shoes.

00:35:35.565 --> 00:35:38.700
 

00:35:38.700 --> 00:35:42.240
So we now have a pending
research proposal

00:35:42.240 --> 00:35:46.110
that we should hear
from the army and DARPA

00:35:46.110 --> 00:35:53.260
from any day now to use current
athletic shoe technology to try

00:35:53.260 --> 00:35:57.110
to make a flexible, variable
compliance socket that's

00:35:57.110 --> 00:36:00.320
stiff in some places
and flexible and others,

00:36:00.320 --> 00:36:02.230
breakable everywhere.

00:36:02.230 --> 00:36:04.390
That basically solves
all the same problems

00:36:04.390 --> 00:36:06.990
that your running shoes do.

00:36:06.990 --> 00:36:10.360
And this would address
the number one reason

00:36:10.360 --> 00:36:13.320
that people abandon
prosthetic arms.

00:36:13.320 --> 00:36:17.100
And that by the way,
actually includes,

00:36:17.100 --> 00:36:20.040
for example one
of the DARPA arms

00:36:20.040 --> 00:36:25.530
that was tested in VA clinics
among transradial patients

00:36:25.530 --> 00:36:27.760
like me.

00:36:27.760 --> 00:36:31.460
Comfort was actually
one of the major reasons

00:36:31.460 --> 00:36:34.410
that I think about
half of those patients

00:36:34.410 --> 00:36:36.840
said that they might not
be interested in having

00:36:36.840 --> 00:36:37.800
one of those new arms.

00:36:37.800 --> 00:36:40.490
So if we solve that
problem, then we

00:36:40.490 --> 00:36:43.650
could potentially make a lot
of the other technology more

00:36:43.650 --> 00:36:45.120
effective, because
will be better

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:46.570
at attaching people's bodies.

00:36:46.570 --> 00:36:50.030
So that's what we're
up to right now.

00:36:50.030 --> 00:36:51.530
An orphan device law.

00:36:51.530 --> 00:36:55.480
So at the time that the orphan
drug law was passed in 1983,

00:36:55.480 --> 00:36:59.950
we had a bipartisan Congress.

00:36:59.950 --> 00:37:05.380
And I think that to imagine
in the current legislative

00:37:05.380 --> 00:37:12.540
environment we can get anything
done may be overoptimistic.

00:37:12.540 --> 00:37:15.980
Although perhaps
in an ideal world,

00:37:15.980 --> 00:37:21.785
we would consider a law that
could increase innovation

00:37:21.785 --> 00:37:24.520
and competition in this space.

00:37:24.520 --> 00:37:28.140
Now for those of you who
are unfamiliar with it,

00:37:28.140 --> 00:37:30.330
what the orphan
drug law does, is

00:37:30.330 --> 00:37:35.650
it extends exclusivity
for a drug company

00:37:35.650 --> 00:37:39.760
who's developed
a product but who

00:37:39.760 --> 00:37:42.920
believes that the
further investment

00:37:42.920 --> 00:37:46.730
necessary to actually bring
a proven drug to market

00:37:46.730 --> 00:37:50.830
is not worth the investment
because their patent--

00:37:50.830 --> 00:37:53.300
the exclusivity available to
them on their original patents

00:37:53.300 --> 00:37:53.800
has expired.

00:37:53.800 --> 00:37:57.420
Drug development is often
a really long process

00:37:57.420 --> 00:38:03.760
and it's a race against the
sun down on the patents.

00:38:03.760 --> 00:38:06.630
Now unfortunately,
I'm not convinced

00:38:06.630 --> 00:38:12.290
that a similar model in the
even much smaller orphan device

00:38:12.290 --> 00:38:13.730
spaces would
actually do anything.

00:38:13.730 --> 00:38:19.500
Because exclusivity in
prosthetic arm patents is often

00:38:19.500 --> 00:38:22.561
abandoned when
people decide to stop

00:38:22.561 --> 00:38:24.810
paying the maintenance on
their prosthetic arm patents

00:38:24.810 --> 00:38:26.690
after seven or 15 years.

00:38:26.690 --> 00:38:29.950
So they're leaving exclusivity
on the table with regard

00:38:29.950 --> 00:38:31.820
to patents in this
space already,

00:38:31.820 --> 00:38:34.630
so would extending it
actually do anything?

00:38:34.630 --> 00:38:36.010
And I'm not convinced it would.

00:38:36.010 --> 00:38:56.060
 

00:38:56.060 --> 00:38:58.865
So since we're not miked in
the audience, the question is--

00:38:58.865 --> 00:39:03.230
is the approval process for
medical devices, prosthetic arm

00:39:03.230 --> 00:39:08.909
specifically similarly
long as it is for drugs?

00:39:08.909 --> 00:39:10.450
That's sort of a
complicated question

00:39:10.450 --> 00:39:13.165
because it depends on
which class of devices

00:39:13.165 --> 00:39:14.040
you're talking about.

00:39:14.040 --> 00:39:18.060
The FDA has three classes of
medical devices, one, two,

00:39:18.060 --> 00:39:19.846
and three.

00:39:19.846 --> 00:39:25.790
The DARPA neural-sensing
system would

00:39:25.790 --> 00:39:28.540
be a class three medical
device because it actually

00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:31.190
involves an internal implant.

00:39:31.190 --> 00:39:36.100
Most prosthetic devices
right now are class one.

00:39:36.100 --> 00:39:38.780
And they're not only class
one, they're class one exempt.

00:39:38.780 --> 00:39:41.238
Which means that they are exempt
from-- there are something

00:39:41.238 --> 00:39:44.080
like seven or eight requirements
for class one devices.

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:48.090
And all but three
of those are ignored

00:39:48.090 --> 00:39:53.120
for this group of class
one exempt devices.

00:39:53.120 --> 00:39:56.890
So in fact and
this is something,

00:39:56.890 --> 00:40:01.330
actually that
there's been some--

00:40:01.330 --> 00:40:03.990
some of the folks who've been
pursuing these new things have

00:40:03.990 --> 00:40:06.040
been assuming, and
they may be right,

00:40:06.040 --> 00:40:09.680
that the FDA is seeking
to regulate prosthetic arm

00:40:09.680 --> 00:40:13.175
stuff more rigorously than
they have in the past.

00:40:13.175 --> 00:40:17.600
 

00:40:17.600 --> 00:40:21.910
There are articulated
myoelectric hands

00:40:21.910 --> 00:40:28.944
that have been brought to
market in the last five years

00:40:28.944 --> 00:40:30.110
that were brought to market.

00:40:30.110 --> 00:40:32.574
All you have to do basically
is announced to the FDA

00:40:32.574 --> 00:40:34.990
that you're going to start
selling these things and do it.

00:40:34.990 --> 00:40:37.573
And if you're going to test it
you just stamp it experimental,

00:40:37.573 --> 00:40:39.930
and you're good to go.

00:40:39.930 --> 00:40:44.490
But nobody wants to invest
hundreds of millions of dollars

00:40:44.490 --> 00:40:46.440
in the creation of a
device unless they're

00:40:46.440 --> 00:40:49.190
sure that they're going
to get away with that.

00:40:49.190 --> 00:40:51.670
And the FDA had
been making noises

00:40:51.670 --> 00:40:53.470
that they were going
to try to bump up

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:55.620
the classification of
some of these things.

00:40:55.620 --> 00:41:01.620
And they also have a requirement
for orthopedic devices,

00:41:01.620 --> 00:41:02.710
which is reasonable.

00:41:02.710 --> 00:41:06.690
It's based on-- so a screw
in an orthopedic implant

00:41:06.690 --> 00:41:09.900
is a class one device that's
a component of a class three

00:41:09.900 --> 00:41:11.700
device, which is the implant.

00:41:11.700 --> 00:41:16.540
And there was a bad
failure in the '80s because

00:41:16.540 --> 00:41:19.890
of the changing of
these class one devices.

00:41:19.890 --> 00:41:24.350
And so the FDA requires that
each class one component

00:41:24.350 --> 00:41:27.356
be separately recertified
with the class three system.

00:41:27.356 --> 00:41:29.480
And if somebody did something
like that for example

00:41:29.480 --> 00:41:35.670
with-- say there's a bolt
that can go through your skin

00:41:35.670 --> 00:41:38.880
into the bone, it's called
osteointegration, a titanium

00:41:38.880 --> 00:41:39.620
bolt.

00:41:39.620 --> 00:41:43.530
And the bolt of course
is a class three device

00:41:43.530 --> 00:41:47.040
because it goes inside the body.

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:51.540
And if they required you
to separately certify

00:41:51.540 --> 00:41:54.670
every prosthetic hand
or foot that you attach

00:41:54.670 --> 00:41:57.150
to one of these systems,
it would effectively

00:41:57.150 --> 00:41:59.000
mean that there
wouldn't be available

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:00.840
because nobody would
bother to do it.

00:42:00.840 --> 00:42:03.750
 

00:42:03.750 --> 00:42:06.750
So actually you bring
up a really great point,

00:42:06.750 --> 00:42:09.790
which is that the FDA is a
really important part of this.

00:42:09.790 --> 00:42:14.650
And some orphan device law, a
hypothetical orphan device law

00:42:14.650 --> 00:42:19.450
or revisions of regulations that
might really impact the space

00:42:19.450 --> 00:42:23.140
should try to remove
some of those barriers

00:42:23.140 --> 00:42:26.350
that actually the
FDA could potentially

00:42:26.350 --> 00:42:29.760
create in trying to
better protect us.

00:42:29.760 --> 00:42:33.700
And then there are humanitarian
exemptions available.

00:42:33.700 --> 00:42:35.760
And so this is
something that I think

00:42:35.760 --> 00:42:37.980
there's further consideration.

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:39.730
So that leads into
the next group

00:42:39.730 --> 00:42:42.380
of things which are
beyond new law, what

00:42:42.380 --> 00:42:45.900
about the interpretation of
existing laws and regulations.

00:42:45.900 --> 00:42:51.430
The Bayh-Dole act
is the law from 1980

00:42:51.430 --> 00:42:52.980
that governs the
government funded

00:42:52.980 --> 00:42:54.529
creation of
intellectual property.

00:42:54.529 --> 00:42:57.070
And the part that most of us
are familiar with if you've ever

00:42:57.070 --> 00:42:59.153
received a government grant
is that the government

00:42:59.153 --> 00:43:02.400
has royalty free, nonexclusive
license to anything

00:43:02.400 --> 00:43:04.740
that they pay you to create.

00:43:04.740 --> 00:43:08.010
But then in order to
encourage economic activity,

00:43:08.010 --> 00:43:12.560
anybody who creates the
stuff has the permission

00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:15.650
to go off and license it,
do whatever they want,

00:43:15.650 --> 00:43:18.100
exploit that intellectual
property on their own,

00:43:18.100 --> 00:43:20.790
as long as they don't
charge any royalties back

00:43:20.790 --> 00:43:22.170
to the government.

00:43:22.170 --> 00:43:24.220
In practice I think some
of this actually goes on

00:43:24.220 --> 00:43:26.630
because if they
fund-- particularly

00:43:26.630 --> 00:43:29.420
weapon systems and stuff
like that-- it's not

00:43:29.420 --> 00:43:32.550
like they segment off what
the intellectual property

00:43:32.550 --> 00:43:33.380
component is.

00:43:33.380 --> 00:43:36.480
It's not like anybody else can
make some of these fighter jets

00:43:36.480 --> 00:43:38.940
or tanks or whatever.

00:43:38.940 --> 00:43:42.390
So the least popular
provision of this law what are

00:43:42.390 --> 00:43:43.951
called march-in rights.

00:43:43.951 --> 00:43:45.700
Which means that if
the government-- there

00:43:45.700 --> 00:43:48.620
are four criteria that could
be met where the government can

00:43:48.620 --> 00:43:52.580
come in and say,
you are not making

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:54.925
use of this intellectual
property the way

00:43:54.925 --> 00:43:57.050
we intended you to, we're
going to take it from you

00:43:57.050 --> 00:43:58.258
and give it to somebody else.

00:43:58.258 --> 00:44:00.780
 

00:44:00.780 --> 00:44:06.710
It has been exercised
very few times, if ever,

00:44:06.710 --> 00:44:10.100
and it's a very popular-- as
you could imagine-- provision

00:44:10.100 --> 00:44:12.990
with people who could get a
lot of government funding.

00:44:12.990 --> 00:44:14.031
How much time do we have?

00:44:14.031 --> 00:44:17.620
 

00:44:17.620 --> 00:44:26.880
So while this law
exists it is something

00:44:26.880 --> 00:44:31.730
that could be made use of
that's on the books already.

00:44:31.730 --> 00:44:37.100
Program managers could
say, OK it's been 15 years,

00:44:37.100 --> 00:44:40.740
you haven't-- you created
a product where we're going

00:44:40.740 --> 00:44:43.750
to find somebody who will,
because our goal is to bring

00:44:43.750 --> 00:44:45.600
something like this to market.

00:44:45.600 --> 00:44:47.530
And another one that
I referenced earlier

00:44:47.530 --> 00:44:50.710
is the Center for Medicare
and Medicaid Services.

00:44:50.710 --> 00:44:54.560
So all these devices and many
medical devices are like this,

00:44:54.560 --> 00:44:59.550
are reimbursed as durable
medical equipment--

00:44:59.550 --> 00:45:04.140
canes, walkers, CPAP machines,
and prosthetic devices.

00:45:04.140 --> 00:45:05.910
And the weirdness
that this creates

00:45:05.910 --> 00:45:07.850
is that the whole
cost of supporting

00:45:07.850 --> 00:45:09.800
the device for something
like five years

00:45:09.800 --> 00:45:12.240
in between replacements,
has to be captured just

00:45:12.240 --> 00:45:15.320
in the provision of the product
at the beginning of its life

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:15.916
cycle.

00:45:15.916 --> 00:45:17.540
All of the appointments
and everything.

00:45:17.540 --> 00:45:21.760
So a prosthetist needs
to be able to to function

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:22.630
based on that.

00:45:22.630 --> 00:45:24.904
The other thing that's
weird about this

00:45:24.904 --> 00:45:26.820
is that there's a perverse
incentive of course

00:45:26.820 --> 00:45:29.150
to provide more
up these products.

00:45:29.150 --> 00:45:34.305
Because if you give
somebody a myoelectric arm,

00:45:34.305 --> 00:45:44.070
it reimburses at $35,000 a
body-powered arm may be $8000.

00:45:44.070 --> 00:45:46.680
And the other thing is that the
way that these reimbursement

00:45:46.680 --> 00:45:49.740
codes are created is that a
company has to demonstrate

00:45:49.740 --> 00:45:52.550
efficacy, and then
they petition CMS.

00:45:52.550 --> 00:45:55.060
 

00:45:55.060 --> 00:45:57.812
So that they have to basically
outlay all of the R&amp;D

00:45:57.812 --> 00:45:59.770
ahead, before they know
if they're going to get

00:45:59.770 --> 00:46:00.310
reimbursed.

00:46:00.310 --> 00:46:04.370
There have been some
recent cases where people

00:46:04.370 --> 00:46:07.770
get the wrong answer back from
CMS and it kills the company.

00:46:07.770 --> 00:46:10.600
A good example is
the iBot wheelchair

00:46:10.600 --> 00:46:13.440
which everybody agrees is
pretty impressive technology.

00:46:13.440 --> 00:46:16.530
That came back as being
excluded to a very

00:46:16.530 --> 00:46:21.490
few pretty serious
disabilities and not

00:46:21.490 --> 00:46:25.540
reimbursable at a rate that
could sustain its manufacturer

00:46:25.540 --> 00:46:28.080
and the company's
closed its doors.

00:46:28.080 --> 00:46:29.560
And so it's actually
up in the air

00:46:29.560 --> 00:46:31.601
what's going to happen to
add to that technology.

00:46:31.601 --> 00:46:34.140
Hopefully DEKA, which
is the creator of it,

00:46:34.140 --> 00:46:36.800
will figure something out.

00:46:36.800 --> 00:46:39.610
So one thing I think
people might do

00:46:39.610 --> 00:46:43.200
would be to create incentives
in reimbursement codes.

00:46:43.200 --> 00:46:46.370
You could create a code
for the performance

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:49.130
of a particular device without
knowing that it existed.

00:46:49.130 --> 00:46:54.600
So I could say a 15 degree
of freedom prosthetic hand

00:46:54.600 --> 00:46:57.450
