00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:08.880
So the question is, I mentioned
that most arm amputees still

00:55:08.880 --> 00:55:13.970
use hooks via the
more complicated

00:55:13.970 --> 00:55:19.360
electrical externally
powered prostheses, and why.

00:55:19.360 --> 00:55:21.460
I think cost is part of it.

00:55:21.460 --> 00:55:24.200
The Affordable Care Act
has changed some of that.

00:55:24.200 --> 00:55:33.240
Before January, a lot of
people with medical insurance

00:55:33.240 --> 00:55:39.400
had lifetime caps of-- in some
cases like $1,500 lifetime cap

00:55:39.400 --> 00:55:41.650
on prosthetics
services-- which isn't

00:55:41.650 --> 00:55:45.060
even enough to get
a single prosthesis.

00:55:45.060 --> 00:55:50.750
And beyond the
expansion of coverage,

00:55:50.750 --> 00:55:53.170
the removal of
the lifetime caps,

00:55:53.170 --> 00:55:59.452
and pre-existing
conditions are huge

00:55:59.452 --> 00:56:00.660
for the prosthetic community.

00:56:00.660 --> 00:56:04.760
So to the extent
that it is monetary,

00:56:04.760 --> 00:56:08.420
the Affordable Care should
change some of that.

00:56:08.420 --> 00:56:11.450
 

00:56:11.450 --> 00:56:17.180
Anecdotally, I don't think
there's any great data on this,

00:56:17.180 --> 00:56:23.060
but I think a lot
of common complaints

00:56:23.060 --> 00:56:26.420
about the myoelectric
prostheses are

00:56:26.420 --> 00:56:33.520
latency, unintended movements,
the speed with which the motors

00:56:33.520 --> 00:56:37.370
move the weight, and then
I think you hit on it--

00:56:37.370 --> 00:56:41.630
function is probably
the primary reason.

00:56:41.630 --> 00:56:48.260
The hook has been famously
described in Ted talks

00:56:48.260 --> 00:56:51.790
as a rubber band and a
hook on the end of a stick.

00:56:51.790 --> 00:56:54.420
But I believe the
bar is actually

00:56:54.420 --> 00:56:55.630
quite a bit higher than that.

00:56:55.630 --> 00:56:59.190
The Dorrance hook is really
kind of a marvel of design.

00:56:59.190 --> 00:57:02.760
It's got a bunch of affordances
kind of built into it.

00:57:02.760 --> 00:57:05.330
You could pick something
up, use it as a hook.

00:57:05.330 --> 00:57:07.680
And then as a split
hook you can open it up

00:57:07.680 --> 00:57:10.470
and use the individual
fingers for different things.

00:57:10.470 --> 00:57:15.830
The little thumb that
has the cable on it--

00:57:15.830 --> 00:57:21.820
put that back up-- the little
thumb that has the cable on it

00:57:21.820 --> 00:57:24.820
can be used to
push things, and is

00:57:24.820 --> 00:57:29.430
the part of the
device that's used

00:57:29.430 --> 00:57:31.330
to wedge a knife and a fork.

00:57:31.330 --> 00:57:33.550
Actually that's a
perfect example,

00:57:33.550 --> 00:57:36.840
is eating with a
knife and a fork.

00:57:36.840 --> 00:57:40.996
With cosmetic coverings
on the myoelectric hands

00:57:40.996 --> 00:57:42.370
they tend to be
slippery and it's

00:57:42.370 --> 00:57:46.720
hard to get a knife and a
fork to set securely in them.

00:57:46.720 --> 00:57:49.070
And this thing is designed
to do exactly that.

00:57:49.070 --> 00:57:51.060
It's got a chiseled
tang in the middle

00:57:51.060 --> 00:57:54.670
so you can stick
a tool in there.

00:57:54.670 --> 00:57:56.450
Or you could wedge
either a knife or fork

00:57:56.450 --> 00:57:59.620
in between the fingers
and over the thumb.

00:57:59.620 --> 00:58:02.250
So I think function
is a lot of it.

