00:58:56.620 --> 00:58:58.716
And it's an easier
problem to solve too.

00:58:58.716 --> 00:59:02.390
 

00:59:02.390 --> 00:59:04.280
Well, Oscar Pistorius
is a great example.

00:59:04.280 --> 00:59:07.820
The cheetah legs make somebody
capable of running close

00:59:07.820 --> 00:59:10.920
to a 10 second hundred.

00:59:10.920 --> 00:59:12.980
Although knees are a problem.

00:59:12.980 --> 00:59:18.010
And Oscar Pistorius is
a below-knee amputee.

00:59:18.010 --> 00:59:21.040
But then among the
powered devices,

00:59:21.040 --> 00:59:23.290
control engineers
who work on legs

00:59:23.290 --> 00:59:27.700
have told me that it's possible
to do reasonable approximations

00:59:27.700 --> 00:59:31.360
of gait with the individual
components not even talking

00:59:31.360 --> 00:59:32.700
to each other.

00:59:32.700 --> 00:59:35.350
Where they just respond to
the external forces and they

00:59:35.350 --> 00:59:39.010
are capable of doing a
pretty good job walking.

00:59:39.010 --> 00:59:43.260
And contrast that to
an arm where just--

00:59:43.260 --> 00:59:45.470
forget the manipulation
stuff-- just

00:59:45.470 --> 00:59:47.860
reach to grasp with a
whole arm for somebody

00:59:47.860 --> 00:59:50.570
up to the shoulder level
involves the coordination

00:59:50.570 --> 00:59:52.920
of all of the joints together.

00:59:52.920 --> 00:59:57.640
So I like to say that if you
imagine that these are legs,

00:59:57.640 --> 01:00:00.490
the arm problem has five of
them on the end of a sixth

01:00:00.490 --> 01:00:02.440
and they all have to
dance together in order

01:00:02.440 --> 01:00:04.630
to do the most basic task
that an arm has to do.

01:00:04.630 --> 01:00:07.250
 

01:00:07.250 --> 01:00:09.270
Yeah and so the
economics are-- I

01:00:09.270 --> 01:00:13.040
